1
00:00:18,880 --> 00:00:22,870
<i>Jan Svankmajer is a Czech filmmaker,</i>
<i>krown for his animation.</i>

2
00:01:09,120 --> 00:01:15,870
THE SVANKMAJERS' lMAGlNlNGS

3
00:01:32,760 --> 00:01:35,790
<i>Jan Svankmajer's work</i>
<i>goes beyond filmmaking.</i>

4
00:01:36,560 --> 00:01:40,830
<i>For more than 30 years</i>
<i>he has worked with his wife Eva,</i>

5
00:01:40,880 --> 00:01:43,710
<i>and their work</i>
<i>is inseparable from their life.</i>

6
00:01:43,760 --> 00:01:45,910
<i>Engraving, painting, collage,</i>

7
00:01:45,960 --> 00:01:48,870
<i>ceramics, invention of objects</i>
<i>and animals, puppets,</i>

8
00:01:48,920 --> 00:01:50,750
<i>poetry and so on.</i>

9
00:01:50,800 --> 00:01:52,910
<i>They work in many different media,</i>

10
00:01:52,960 --> 00:01:56,150
<i>but always as a response to surrealism.</i>

11
00:01:57,640 --> 00:02:01,310
<i>As secret members of the surrealist group</i>
<i>in communist Prague,</i>

12
00:02:01,360 --> 00:02:05,060
<i>since the Velvet Revolution</i>
<i>they have beer working tirelessly.</i>

13
00:02:08,920 --> 00:02:13,550
<i>Last winter they interrupted work</i>
<i>on their new film</i>  Little Otik,

14
00:02:13,600 --> 00:02:16,950
<i>to organise an exhibition</i>
<i>showing their body of work.</i>

15
00:02:21,680 --> 00:02:23,150
HUMAN ANATOMY

16
00:02:43,480 --> 00:02:46,150
NATURAL HlSTORY

17
00:03:17,640 --> 00:03:21,230
And over there are the collages.

18
00:03:21,280 --> 00:03:23,150
Yes, those are the collages.

19
00:03:23,720 --> 00:03:27,030
Some of them are new,
some are of disjointed anatomy.

20
00:03:27,080 --> 00:03:32,590
- But those are new things?
- Yes, also.

21
00:03:33,280 --> 00:03:38,790
l found inexpensive, second-hand
anatomical atlases.

22
00:03:38,840 --> 00:03:42,380
l couldn't resist cutting them up.

23
00:03:42,440 --> 00:03:44,230
Although it's a bit...

24
00:04:17,920 --> 00:04:21,620
Some objects travel
from one film to another

25
00:04:21,680 --> 00:04:27,390
or from another art form to a film
or conversely from a film to another art form.

26
00:04:31,400 --> 00:04:33,780
l think there is only one sort of poetry

27
00:04:33,840 --> 00:04:38,110
and that the form of expression
of that poetry is not that important,

28
00:04:38,160 --> 00:04:43,790
whether it's film, painting,
engraving, collage or ceramics.

29
00:04:44,320 --> 00:04:49,310
lt's professional laziness
to only use one form of expression.

30
00:04:49,360 --> 00:04:53,110
ln that respect l consider myself
to be a militant surrealist.

31
00:04:53,640 --> 00:04:56,390
<i>The Felaceus Oedipus or 'false Oedipus'</i>

32
00:04:56,440 --> 00:04:59,670
<i>is an extremely rare species found</i>
<i>on the edge of the Australian bush.</i>

33
00:05:00,960 --> 00:05:03,750
<i>Its neck extends</i>
<i>from a giant elastic pouch,</i>

34
00:05:03,800 --> 00:05:07,550
<i>A bony thorax rises</i>
<i>from the upperpart of the neck.</i>

35
00:05:07,600 --> 00:05:10,390
<i>The Australian Aborigenes</i>
<i>call the bird 'Maca Samambo',</i>

36
00:05:10,440 --> 00:05:13,070
<i>which means 'giver of sons'.</i>

37
00:05:13,120 --> 00:05:16,110
<i>They believe that</i>
<i>if a pregnant woman eats one of its eggs,</i>,

38
00:05:16,160 --> 00:05:17,950
<i>she will give birth to a son.</i>

39
00:05:18,560 --> 00:05:22,630
<i>And the Felaceus Oedipus' eggs</i>
<i>hatch into male chicks</i>,

40
00:05:22,680 --> 00:05:24,870
<i>which are born penis first.</i>

41
00:05:55,240 --> 00:05:58,550
<i>There was once a man and a woman</i>
<i>who didn't have any children,</i>

42
00:05:58,600 --> 00:06:00,390
<i>which made them very urhappy.</i>

43
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:06,300
<i>One day the man went into the forest</i>

44
00:06:06,360 --> 00:06:09,390
<i>and there he found a root</i>
<i>in the shape of a little boy.</i>

45
00:06:10,120 --> 00:06:13,350
<i>He took it back to his wife</i>
<i>and they called it Otesánek</i>

46
00:07:02,120 --> 00:07:06,150
We are cutting various shapes
of Otesánek's body

47
00:07:06,200 --> 00:07:08,150
for different stages of the animation.

48
00:07:08,200 --> 00:07:12,110
We need the legs
to have different positions,

49
00:07:12,160 --> 00:07:16,470
the branches as legs
in different positions

50
00:07:16,520 --> 00:07:20,950
so we can make them move
as Otesánek moves.

51
00:07:27,280 --> 00:07:29,350
And what's that for?

52
00:07:30,440 --> 00:07:34,710
That's to animate the facial expressions.

53
00:07:35,880 --> 00:07:38,590
We choose different shapes
with different orifices

54
00:07:38,640 --> 00:07:44,270
because afterwards they become eyes or teeth,
orifices where light disappears.

55
00:07:45,240 --> 00:07:49,550
We want to make Otesánek's expressions
out of real pieces of wood.

56
00:08:09,200 --> 00:08:13,710
There are still lots of Otesáneks
to be made here.

57
00:08:13,760 --> 00:08:16,870
For example,
this piece of wood has a lovely penis.

58
00:08:21,880 --> 00:08:25,790
We have chosen to create the movement
in different stages.

59
00:08:25,840 --> 00:08:29,110
There are some with their legs apart,

60
00:08:29,160 --> 00:08:31,990
others with one leg
or with both legs together.

61
00:08:32,600 --> 00:08:36,590
And we're going to film all that

62
00:08:36,640 --> 00:08:39,270
in sequences of two images
to create movement.

63
00:08:41,360 --> 00:08:44,510
We made this one sitting down

64
00:08:44,560 --> 00:08:49,500
so the mother can hold it in her arms.

65
00:08:49,560 --> 00:08:52,630
For the animation,
they will be done differently,

66
00:08:52,680 --> 00:08:57,830
clothed and made of lead wire.

67
00:08:57,880 --> 00:09:03,950
Fingers and hands will be animated,
the legs and head will move.

68
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:06,430
This stage is between that one -

69
00:09:09,280 --> 00:09:13,550
its legs are closer together which is good -

70
00:09:13,600 --> 00:09:15,390
- and this stage.

71
00:09:31,640 --> 00:09:35,830
l think we should have enough stages.

72
00:09:35,880 --> 00:09:39,580
lf we add the two completed Otesáneks
we have over there,

73
00:09:39,640 --> 00:09:42,230
l think that should be enough.

74
00:09:49,320 --> 00:09:51,620
l'll chop it into pieces!

75
00:09:52,760 --> 00:09:54,150
You've gone mad!

76
00:09:54,360 --> 00:09:56,870
You've gone mad. l won't let you.

77
00:10:22,120 --> 00:10:25,790
Martin, there's one there on that side.

78
00:10:26,520 --> 00:10:29,630
There on that side.

79
00:10:37,560 --> 00:10:42,950
A feature of these pine roots
is that they look like little fingers.

80
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:48,350
We're going to use them
to make Otesánek's fingers and toes.

81
00:10:48,400 --> 00:10:51,110
So we've come here
to look for fingers and toes.

82
00:10:58,200 --> 00:11:01,510
The roots can go up and then disappear.

83
00:11:23,200 --> 00:11:25,110
We can start.

84
00:11:30,720 --> 00:11:31,780
The shoulder!

85
00:11:33,720 --> 00:11:34,550
ls it going?

86
00:11:38,360 --> 00:11:39,470
Otesánek!

87
00:11:42,680 --> 00:11:48,190
We're using classical techniques
to animate <i>Little Otik</i>

88
00:11:48,240 --> 00:11:53,990
We're going to combine animation
in close-up shots

89
00:11:54,040 --> 00:11:59,230
with techniques
using puppets on nylon strings.

90
00:12:00,840 --> 00:12:05,510
And we're going
to combine that with shots

91
00:12:05,560 --> 00:12:12,390
where someone is inside Otesánek
with gloves made like little roots.

92
00:12:12,440 --> 00:12:17,110
He moves his hands,
his fingers, the roots.

93
00:12:17,160 --> 00:12:20,860
So we combine
those classical techniques.

94
00:12:20,920 --> 00:12:22,430
That's the best way because...

95
00:12:22,480 --> 00:12:28,110
because before the spectator can grasp
how each picture is made

96
00:12:28,160 --> 00:12:29,550
the technique changes again.

97
00:12:29,600 --> 00:12:33,590
So he's been tricked

98
00:12:33,640 --> 00:12:36,630
and can't work out how we did it.

99
00:12:58,160 --> 00:13:02,150
lf you move something
when animating the roots,

100
00:13:02,200 --> 00:13:04,110
you'll have to work with it...

101
00:13:04,160 --> 00:13:06,910
ls it more difficult to animate
real wood than latex?

102
00:13:09,080 --> 00:13:12,700
ln some ways
it's a bit more complicated

103
00:13:12,760 --> 00:13:16,270
but on the other hand,
the material implies its own movement

104
00:13:16,320 --> 00:13:21,230
so, in a sense, the material cooperates.

105
00:13:21,280 --> 00:13:25,230
lt's not the stylisation of an object.

106
00:13:25,280 --> 00:13:27,470
So it's more difficult.

107
00:13:27,520 --> 00:13:32,150
But l prefer it
because it's kind of natural.

108
00:13:33,800 --> 00:13:36,260
Animating Otesánek
is physically demanding!

109
00:14:05,520 --> 00:14:06,630
<i>Leave that</i>

110
00:14:06,680 --> 00:14:08,310
<i>Don't do that</i>

111
00:14:08,360 --> 00:14:10,030
<i>Why don't you listen to me?</i>

112
00:14:10,080 --> 00:14:12,030
<i>Don't tear it.</i>

113
00:14:12,080 --> 00:14:13,220
<i>What did l tell you?</i>

114
00:14:14,120 --> 00:14:16,680
What do you think
of computer animation?

115
00:14:16,720 --> 00:14:20,950
l haven't used it so far.
What l've seen up to now seems

116
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:25,110
to be very cold,
very technical, very distant.

117
00:14:25,160 --> 00:14:29,070
All that l've needed
to do up until now

118
00:14:29,120 --> 00:14:33,350
l have done using classical,
manual techniques,

119
00:14:33,400 --> 00:14:36,910
including the film <i>Food</i>
where the characters...

120
00:14:36,960 --> 00:14:39,670
are devouring the tables and chairs

121
00:14:39,720 --> 00:14:41,670
and we see their heads change.

122
00:14:41,720 --> 00:14:46,190
All that was done with modelling clay.

123
00:14:54,400 --> 00:14:57,510
lt's not that l am a lover
of the days gone by

124
00:14:57,560 --> 00:15:02,070
but l don't like these techniques
because there's something missing.

125
00:15:02,120 --> 00:15:06,070
lt's too perfect.
The technique is too garish.

126
00:15:06,120 --> 00:15:09,270
Whereas with manual animation,
it's less precise.

127
00:15:09,320 --> 00:15:16,070
There are lots of little
imperfections and mistakes

128
00:15:16,120 --> 00:15:21,950
and for me mistakes are very important

129
00:15:22,000 --> 00:15:27,830
because they make the film subjective.

130
00:15:37,320 --> 00:15:41,100
Like the ancient Hermeticists,

131
00:15:41,160 --> 00:15:43,620
l believe that objects
have a life of their own.

132
00:15:43,680 --> 00:15:49,590
And because
they have witnessed certain events,

133
00:15:49,640 --> 00:15:52,910
or rather because
they've been handled by people

134
00:15:52,960 --> 00:15:57,590
who were in a certain frame of mind,
who were tense or anxious,

135
00:15:57,640 --> 00:16:01,990
and these objects have absorbed all that

136
00:16:02,040 --> 00:16:08,590
and in certain situations objects
can convey what they have absorbed.

137
00:16:08,640 --> 00:16:12,550
So based on what l feel they contain,
l collect these objects

138
00:16:12,600 --> 00:16:14,900
and introduce them into my films.

139
00:16:23,720 --> 00:16:25,950
THE CELLAR

140
00:16:45,360 --> 00:16:49,390
Places haunt me as much as themes.

141
00:16:49,440 --> 00:16:55,030
One of the most haunting themes
is the cellar.

142
00:16:55,080 --> 00:17:00,910
l really suffered as a child
when l had to go down there.

143
00:17:01,720 --> 00:17:06,070
The cellar in <i>Alice</i>
and of course in <i>Little Otik</i>  too,

144
00:17:06,120 --> 00:17:08,580
is the cellar from my childhood.

145
00:17:08,640 --> 00:17:13,470
There was a cellar like that
in our block of flats in Vrsovice.

146
00:17:29,160 --> 00:17:31,590
My mother sent me down to the cellar

147
00:17:31,640 --> 00:17:34,910
to fetch coal when l was older
and before that to fetch potatoes.

148
00:17:35,960 --> 00:17:38,070
lt was, of course...

149
00:17:39,480 --> 00:17:41,190
a terrifying experience.

150
00:17:45,840 --> 00:17:47,550
lt was awful.

151
00:17:47,600 --> 00:17:54,030
When my mother asked me
to go down to the cellar for potatoes,

152
00:17:55,560 --> 00:18:00,750
l almost felt like
running away from home.

153
00:18:01,960 --> 00:18:05,870
But at the same time,
it fed my imagination.

154
00:18:07,560 --> 00:18:10,390
Why did you choose to use a little girl

155
00:18:10,440 --> 00:18:11,830
to represent your fear?

156
00:18:11,880 --> 00:18:16,150
lt didn't feel right to use
a little boy in that role

157
00:18:16,200 --> 00:18:20,350
because l thought
that my anxiety was linked

158
00:18:20,400 --> 00:18:25,420
to the feminine side that exists in a man.

159
00:18:25,480 --> 00:18:29,790
So l decided to replace myself

160
00:18:29,840 --> 00:18:33,350
with a sort of childlike
incarnation of my spirit.

161
00:19:22,960 --> 00:19:25,470
These objects are from the film <i>Alice</i>

162
00:19:25,520 --> 00:19:27,980
There you have croissants with nails

163
00:19:28,040 --> 00:19:32,710
and these are eggs with skulls.
lt's marinated in something.

164
00:19:32,760 --> 00:19:37,510
Some eggs are probably bad
and if we were to uncork the bottle,

165
00:19:37,600 --> 00:19:39,150
it would stink.

166
00:19:39,200 --> 00:19:42,790
Look, it's rotten there.

167
00:19:58,320 --> 00:19:59,950
That's from the film <i>Alice</i>

168
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:02,910
This is classic putrefaction.

169
00:20:02,960 --> 00:20:05,950
These are the shoes worn
by the cameraman on <i>Alice</i>

170
00:20:06,000 --> 00:20:09,230
They've been in here since 1986.

171
00:20:09,280 --> 00:20:13,670
lt's hermetically sealed

172
00:20:14,720 --> 00:20:17,350
and they're slowly rotting inside.

173
00:20:33,160 --> 00:20:35,590
We're going to put this one here

174
00:20:36,560 --> 00:20:39,590
and the other one against the wall.

175
00:21:00,880 --> 00:21:02,510
Here are the king and queen.

176
00:21:02,560 --> 00:21:06,670
Eva has depicted herself
as the wicked queen.

177
00:21:07,040 --> 00:21:08,790
<i>Off with their heads!'</i>

178
00:21:08,840 --> 00:21:10,550
<i>ordered the Queen.</i>

179
00:21:21,800 --> 00:21:24,710
This is the March Hare

180
00:21:24,760 --> 00:21:28,510
and this is the Mad Hatter.

181
00:21:28,560 --> 00:21:30,150
They're the characters in <i>Alice</i>

182
00:21:33,640 --> 00:21:37,150
Eva made the hare and l made this one.

183
00:22:24,200 --> 00:22:26,390
CREATlVE DlALOGUE

184
00:22:26,440 --> 00:22:27,470
Can it be washed?

185
00:22:27,520 --> 00:22:34,750
lt can't. l can scrub it
but water won't clean it.

186
00:22:34,800 --> 00:22:39,070
All along l carry an idea about the film.

187
00:22:39,120 --> 00:22:40,950
l also have an idea

188
00:22:41,040 --> 00:22:45,230
and of where l come in,
what l will do.

189
00:22:45,280 --> 00:22:49,830
l try my hardest
to understand what Jan wants.

190
00:22:50,320 --> 00:22:53,350
I don't know how to copy.

191
00:22:53,400 --> 00:22:57,830
l have my own personal expression.
l've had it for years...

192
00:22:57,880 --> 00:22:59,830
Of course, l give Eva free reign.

193
00:22:59,880 --> 00:23:02,990
What l want from her is

194
00:23:03,040 --> 00:23:07,390
within the framework
of her own thinking, her own creativity.

195
00:23:07,440 --> 00:23:10,000
She fits in
without forcing herself.

196
00:23:10,040 --> 00:23:15,830
l can't say to her,
'l want that redder,' or 'bigger'.

197
00:23:24,240 --> 00:23:30,710
Eva did a lot of work as a painter
on <i>The Pendulum, the Pit and Hope.</i>

198
00:23:30,760 --> 00:23:34,540
She made the moving wall,

199
00:23:36,440 --> 00:23:41,430
the panels which represent hell

200
00:23:41,480 --> 00:23:44,790
and push the condemned into the abyss.

201
00:23:57,320 --> 00:24:01,790
To sum up the collaborative process,

202
00:24:01,840 --> 00:24:03,550
Eva has her own creative programme.

203
00:24:03,600 --> 00:24:06,590
She is a painter,
she writes prose and poetry.

204
00:24:07,320 --> 00:24:09,510
We work independently of each other.

205
00:24:09,560 --> 00:24:11,830
We are linked by surrealism

206
00:24:11,880 --> 00:24:13,950
but that's another matter.

207
00:24:14,480 --> 00:24:16,910
Once l broke one

208
00:24:16,960 --> 00:24:20,990
because people was watching me.
I needed them to go away,

209
00:24:21,040 --> 00:24:25,670
so that l did not have to see
them seeing me.

210
00:24:26,560 --> 00:24:27,910
Leave me alone.

211
00:24:37,160 --> 00:24:40,070
l can see you're very good at group sex!

212
00:24:40,120 --> 00:24:41,750
Oh, no!

213
00:24:41,800 --> 00:24:47,350
Once someone l knew
invited me to an orgy

214
00:24:47,400 --> 00:24:49,470
and l got such a shock

215
00:24:49,520 --> 00:24:52,550
that he never suggested it again.

216
00:24:53,720 --> 00:24:55,590
They are placed around the outside.

217
00:24:57,600 --> 00:24:59,950
- That's impossible.
- Leave it.

218
00:25:00,000 --> 00:25:01,550
l'll position that one.

219
00:25:03,800 --> 00:25:06,790
lf you numbered them they must...

220
00:25:06,840 --> 00:25:08,030
You'll break it.

221
00:25:09,600 --> 00:25:10,710
That's not the way.

222
00:25:10,760 --> 00:25:13,140
That's number five. lt can't go there.

223
00:25:13,200 --> 00:25:15,030
But this one belongs here.

224
00:25:15,080 --> 00:25:16,430
OK, OK.

225
00:25:16,480 --> 00:25:19,430
This one fits in here.
You'll break it.

226
00:25:19,480 --> 00:25:23,180
That's number two. lt goes there.

227
00:25:23,240 --> 00:25:26,310
l put them wrong yesterday.

228
00:25:28,640 --> 00:25:29,590
Right...

229
00:25:29,640 --> 00:25:30,830
Wait!

230
00:25:31,560 --> 00:25:33,750
You're messing it up.

231
00:25:33,800 --> 00:25:35,390
Again. Take them all off.

232
00:25:35,440 --> 00:25:37,430
We'll have to start again.

233
00:25:41,320 --> 00:25:43,350
That one should be in front.

234
00:25:46,480 --> 00:25:47,870
Eva.

235
00:25:47,920 --> 00:25:51,670
Shouldn't they be the other way round?

236
00:25:51,720 --> 00:25:52,700
What?

237
00:25:52,760 --> 00:25:55,470
That one should be in front
and that one behind.

238
00:25:56,600 --> 00:25:58,230
That one has to be in front.

239
00:25:58,280 --> 00:26:02,110
l prefer not to see it.

240
00:26:02,160 --> 00:26:04,590
Well, put some cloth over it.

241
00:26:05,680 --> 00:26:09,380
We're always trying
to say something to each other.

242
00:26:09,440 --> 00:26:14,030
We're always curious
of what the other's attitude will be...

243
00:26:14,080 --> 00:26:16,830
how they will react.

244
00:26:16,880 --> 00:26:18,550
lt broadens the perspective.

245
00:26:21,640 --> 00:26:23,390
There we go. At last.

246
00:26:32,640 --> 00:26:35,310
Why do you sign your ceramics E and J?

247
00:26:35,360 --> 00:26:37,790
The initials E and J
distinguish between things

248
00:26:37,840 --> 00:26:41,430
made by Jan and by me.

249
00:26:41,480 --> 00:26:43,830
We work with the same materials,

250
00:26:43,880 --> 00:26:45,670
we share the same life

251
00:26:45,720 --> 00:26:50,550
but we express ourselves differently,

252
00:26:50,600 --> 00:26:53,590
not in terms of ideas...

253
00:26:53,640 --> 00:26:57,470
nor in terms of our interpretation of life,

254
00:26:57,520 --> 00:27:00,190
but the art we create is different.

255
00:27:00,240 --> 00:27:04,070
Our work is not interchangeable.

256
00:27:05,800 --> 00:27:08,670
How did you work together on <i>Little Otik</i>?

257
00:27:08,720 --> 00:27:10,950
Eva really liked
the story of 'Otesánek'.

258
00:27:11,000 --> 00:27:15,860
She wanted to make it
into an animated film

259
00:27:15,920 --> 00:27:18,070
and she wrote a script.

260
00:27:21,160 --> 00:27:22,670
l tried to dissuade her

261
00:27:24,000 --> 00:27:27,230
but Eva was already working on it,

262
00:27:27,280 --> 00:27:30,790
and because of the transfer
of thought processes

263
00:27:30,840 --> 00:27:33,430
that passes between two people
who live together...

264
00:27:33,480 --> 00:27:37,830
l was very sceptical to start with

265
00:27:37,880 --> 00:27:42,030
about the idea of making a film of a fairytale.

266
00:27:43,680 --> 00:27:50,020
Then suddenly l found myself
thinking also about the subject.

267
00:27:50,080 --> 00:27:51,990
lt started taking shape in my head.

268
00:27:52,040 --> 00:27:56,790
And l said to myself,
'Christ, l can't steal this idea from Eva.'

269
00:27:57,320 --> 00:28:04,820
But l had delved so deeply
into the subject

270
00:28:04,880 --> 00:28:11,140
that l couldn't stop developing it further.

271
00:28:11,200 --> 00:28:14,550
l was presented with a dilemma
and l didn't know what to do.

272
00:28:14,600 --> 00:28:20,310
So l admitted to her
that l wanted to work on 'Otesánek' too.

273
00:28:20,360 --> 00:28:22,820
She got a bit angry.

274
00:28:22,880 --> 00:28:27,390
Then we realised
that there was no conflict of interests

275
00:28:27,440 --> 00:28:31,060
and that we could incorporate
her film in mine.

276
00:28:31,920 --> 00:28:35,830
<i>One morning the man dug up</i>
<i>a little tree stump in the forest.</i>

277
00:28:35,880 --> 00:28:38,310
<i>It looked like a little child.</i>

278
00:28:39,160 --> 00:28:43,870
<i>He just had to cut the roots</i>
<i>into hands and legs.</i>

279
00:28:50,240 --> 00:28:53,510
