00:32:22,520 --> 00:32:24,070
Like that. Against him. Yes.

326
00:33:40,800 --> 00:33:43,790
THE PERFECT PALACE

327
00:33:52,080 --> 00:33:54,380
<i>Tuesday 17 July</i>

328
00:33:54,440 --> 00:33:58,830
<i>My cameraman and his wife Anna</i>
<i>came to our house in Stankov.</i>

329
00:34:02,680 --> 00:34:07,070
<i>Having done a tour of the castle,</i>
<i>Anna made the following observation:</i>

330
00:34:07,120 --> 00:34:12,060
<i>'You're transforming Stankov</i>
<i>into a puppet theatre'. She had a point.</i>

331
00:34:14,200 --> 00:34:18,390
<i>I think what we had done with Stankov</i>
<i>was an amazing feat in its own way.</i>

332
00:34:19,240 --> 00:34:21,800
<i>I hope we will have the courage</i>
<i>to see it through.</i>

333
00:34:23,040 --> 00:34:26,030
<i>We need to build something</i>
<i>somewhere between Kuks Castle</i>

334
00:34:26,080 --> 00:34:28,590
<i>and the postman Cheval's Perfect Palace -</i>

335
00:34:28,640 --> 00:34:31,470
<i>a kind of surrealist home for sages.</i>

336
00:34:32,200 --> 00:34:34,910
<i>It's going to need ever more concertration</i>

337
00:34:34,960 --> 00:34:37,190
<i>and more intersive work.</i>

338
00:34:37,760 --> 00:34:40,590
<i>We should draw up a plan</i>
<i>for the finished project.</i>

339
00:34:41,320 --> 00:34:43,150
<i>Ever at the stage it's at row,</i>

340
00:34:43,200 --> 00:34:46,350
<i> I think it could be a project</i>
<i>that will take your breath away.</i>

341
00:34:46,400 --> 00:34:47,990
<i>But I don't know what to do.</i>

342
00:35:23,640 --> 00:35:25,870
lt's terribly neglected.

343
00:35:29,720 --> 00:35:32,310
Why do you surround yourself with statues?

344
00:35:32,360 --> 00:35:34,510
That's a stupid question.

345
00:35:40,360 --> 00:35:43,030
How can you live without statues?

346
00:35:43,080 --> 00:35:45,110
Without trees, without water?

347
00:35:45,160 --> 00:35:49,350
Perhaps because life
without sculptures is meaningless.

348
00:35:49,400 --> 00:35:51,390
Perhaps because sculptures,

349
00:35:51,440 --> 00:35:55,390
like trees and things that last,

350
00:35:55,440 --> 00:35:58,390
are essential to life.

351
00:35:58,440 --> 00:36:00,900
l can't say why l put statues somewhere.

352
00:36:02,200 --> 00:36:03,590
l can't.

353
00:36:03,640 --> 00:36:06,310
Why is Jan fascinated by Arcimboldo?

354
00:36:07,880 --> 00:36:09,470
l can't answer that.

355
00:36:09,520 --> 00:36:11,630
You'll have to ask him.

356
00:36:13,480 --> 00:36:17,790
<i>Today I spent all day in the studio</i>
<i>making a new Arcimboldo.</i>

357
00:36:22,160 --> 00:36:25,030
<i>It's terrible but I find this activity</i>
<i>as exciting as ever,</i>

358
00:36:25,080 --> 00:36:27,430
<i>and I'll probably never understand why.</i>

359
00:36:41,320 --> 00:36:45,020
SURREALlSM
AGAlNST THE TlDE

360
00:36:52,560 --> 00:36:55,830
At the end of the '60s,
especially with the Prague Spring,

361
00:36:56,960 --> 00:37:01,550
we were able to organise one or two exhibitions
and publish a few things.

362
00:37:01,600 --> 00:37:06,350
Then with the Soviet occupation
the group went back underground.

363
00:37:12,480 --> 00:37:14,750
Here there was a big table

364
00:37:14,800 --> 00:37:18,500
and we would sit here with the group.

365
00:37:18,560 --> 00:37:23,790
The whole house was given over
to our surrealist activities.

366
00:37:23,840 --> 00:37:28,030
The whole house almost all the time.

367
00:37:28,080 --> 00:37:30,230
There was always someone sleeping there.

368
00:37:30,280 --> 00:37:33,980
We had meetings every week.

369
00:37:35,400 --> 00:37:37,700
We did that for years,
until the revolution.

370
00:37:37,760 --> 00:37:41,990
Before, when we met in a cafe,

371
00:37:42,640 --> 00:37:45,470
we could be sure that at the third meeting,

372
00:37:45,520 --> 00:37:47,820
not the second but the third,

373
00:37:47,880 --> 00:37:51,190
that at the next table

374
00:37:51,240 --> 00:37:53,510
there would be a man in an raincoat

375
00:37:53,560 --> 00:37:56,230
drinking beer slowly,

376
00:37:56,280 --> 00:37:58,390
without looking at us.

377
00:37:59,280 --> 00:38:03,150
So we said, 'We can't talk here.

378
00:38:03,200 --> 00:38:04,870
We'll meet at the house.'

379
00:38:23,040 --> 00:38:26,550
To a certain extent,
we were against Stalinism

380
00:38:26,600 --> 00:38:30,750
as well as against other dissidents.

381
00:38:38,760 --> 00:38:41,060
We were involved,
we communicated

382
00:38:41,880 --> 00:38:45,030
with Havel, for example,

383
00:38:45,080 --> 00:38:47,750
and with dissidents

384
00:38:47,800 --> 00:38:49,950
who now hold political posts.

385
00:38:50,000 --> 00:38:51,590
For 20 years

386
00:38:51,640 --> 00:38:56,070
we illegally created
the real Czech culture.

387
00:39:00,920 --> 00:39:04,460
When the totalitarian system
came to an end,

388
00:39:04,520 --> 00:39:06,070
everyone dispersed.

389
00:39:06,120 --> 00:39:09,030
Dissidents dispersed,
the underground movement broke up,

390
00:39:09,080 --> 00:39:11,640
but the surrealist group stayed together.

391
00:39:11,680 --> 00:39:14,670
ln the '50s

392
00:39:14,720 --> 00:39:19,190
l had a manual and on the back page
there was a portrait of Gottwald,

393
00:39:19,240 --> 00:39:22,830
who was the President
of Czechoslovakia,

394
00:39:22,880 --> 00:39:24,870
as well as a portrait of Stalin.

395
00:39:25,400 --> 00:39:31,430
For me these two men
were personal enemies

396
00:39:31,480 --> 00:39:35,550
because they endangered
my family and my future.

397
00:39:35,600 --> 00:39:38,790
l come from a rich family

398
00:39:38,840 --> 00:39:43,630
and my only prospect was
to become a chimney sweep...

399
00:39:44,840 --> 00:39:46,470
or a miner

400
00:39:46,520 --> 00:39:49,550
and something else like that.
l can't remember.

401
00:39:49,600 --> 00:39:51,830
Equally ghastly.

402
00:39:51,880 --> 00:39:53,910
l'm a hard worker,

403
00:39:53,960 --> 00:39:57,870
l don't mind crawling into a chimney
or digging coal. That's OK by me.

404
00:39:57,920 --> 00:40:02,590
But what l objected to was the terrible...

405
00:40:03,280 --> 00:40:06,190
deculturisation of society

406
00:40:06,240 --> 00:40:11,100
and l felt despair at the idea

407
00:40:11,200 --> 00:40:16,220
that one day someone might wrestle
my pencil or pen out of my hand.

408
00:40:16,280 --> 00:40:18,840
l left school at 14 and said to myself

409
00:40:18,880 --> 00:40:22,190
that no-one would ever snatch my pen off me.

410
00:40:22,240 --> 00:40:25,430
lt was hard, but no-one ever did.

411
00:40:49,880 --> 00:40:51,390
The regime has changed

412
00:40:51,440 --> 00:40:55,390
and for ten years people have been
encouraged to be interested only in money.

413
00:40:57,280 --> 00:40:58,950
lt's the same thing.

414
00:41:00,520 --> 00:41:02,900
Whenever l say l'm a surrealist

415
00:41:02,960 --> 00:41:05,550
l get pitying looks...

416
00:41:05,600 --> 00:41:10,430
People think, 'Those poor people
who lived under communist rule,

417
00:41:10,480 --> 00:41:14,070
they don't know that surrealism
is no longer fashionable.'

418
00:41:14,120 --> 00:41:18,150
They tolerate my declaration

419
00:41:18,200 --> 00:41:21,310
but as soon as we start discussing it,

420
00:41:22,680 --> 00:41:24,630
especially with young people,

421
00:41:25,640 --> 00:41:27,630
they start getting interested

422
00:41:27,680 --> 00:41:31,150
because they understand there's more to it

423
00:41:31,200 --> 00:41:33,910
than Salvador Dalí's paintings.

424
00:41:43,920 --> 00:41:46,030
Young people
are interested in my films.

425
00:41:46,080 --> 00:41:48,910
They realise
that there's more to surrealism

426
00:41:48,960 --> 00:41:52,630
than they've learnt at school
and been told about.

427
00:41:52,680 --> 00:41:54,790
They say to themselves,

428
00:41:54,840 --> 00:41:58,190
'lf that's what surrealism is,

429
00:41:58,240 --> 00:42:03,070
then it's not dead,
because l'm interested in it.'

430
00:42:24,840 --> 00:42:26,870
FOOD

431
00:43:00,640 --> 00:43:04,180
l was a very thin child
who needed to be fed constantly.

432
00:43:04,240 --> 00:43:06,620
l was forced to eat,

433
00:43:06,680 --> 00:43:12,110
l was sent to camps to be fed.

434
00:43:12,920 --> 00:43:19,100
The only aim of these camps
was to force-feed kids.

435
00:43:19,920 --> 00:43:22,590
lt was terrible.

436
00:43:22,640 --> 00:43:28,110
lf a child put on a kilo in a week,

437
00:43:28,760 --> 00:43:30,350
they got a sweet.

438
00:43:32,120 --> 00:43:35,030
So each week
before we were weighed,

439
00:43:35,080 --> 00:43:38,670
we drank loads of water
so as to put on a kilo.

440
00:43:39,440 --> 00:43:43,190
Of course this was in collaboration
with the political regime

441
00:43:43,240 --> 00:43:47,310
which was there to help everyone,
including skinny children.

442
00:43:47,360 --> 00:43:48,390
lt was terrible.

443
00:43:48,440 --> 00:43:51,430
We were kids separated from our families

444
00:43:51,480 --> 00:43:55,350
and we spent two months there

445
00:43:55,400 --> 00:43:58,870
at the hands of women
who force-fed us constantly.

446
00:43:58,920 --> 00:44:02,270
They even refused to put me
in the top class

447
00:44:02,320 --> 00:44:04,270
because l was too thin.

448
00:44:04,320 --> 00:44:08,790
l even ended up in a wheelchair
because l couldn't walk any more.

449
00:44:09,320 --> 00:44:12,750
lt was a traumatic experience

450
00:44:12,800 --> 00:44:16,340
and of course l used it in my films.

451
00:44:18,600 --> 00:44:21,590
The meal is naturally symbolic.

452
00:44:22,760 --> 00:44:26,540
Food and eating are symbols of...

453
00:44:29,480 --> 00:44:31,590
human aggressiveness.

454
00:44:42,120 --> 00:44:47,550
And yet it was only when l had finished
writing the screenplay for <i>Little Otik</i>

455
00:44:47,600 --> 00:44:52,750
that l realised that the whole film
was about my obsession with food.

456
00:44:57,080 --> 00:44:59,460
<i>Otik, drop that! Don't eat that!</i>

457
00:44:59,520 --> 00:45:03,390
We're going to add a bit more bark

458
00:45:03,440 --> 00:45:07,110
to make it more realistic.

459
00:45:07,160 --> 00:45:10,910
Then we'll do a close-up with the teeth.

460
00:45:12,080 --> 00:45:15,150
But l don't have any rational control
over my obsessions.

461
00:45:15,200 --> 00:45:20,990
They behave in an irrational way
and do what they want to do.

462
00:45:29,520 --> 00:45:32,910
Otesánek could of course
also represent our unconscious.

463
00:45:39,240 --> 00:45:46,920
We know that fairytales
start out as myths -

464
00:45:46,960 --> 00:45:51,230
either cosmic myths

465
00:45:52,000 --> 00:45:54,380
or social myths,
but myths all the same.

466
00:45:54,440 --> 00:45:58,190
Otesánek is definitely an archetype.

467
00:45:58,240 --> 00:45:59,830
And that's what interests me,

468
00:45:59,880 --> 00:46:05,510
going to the root of what
Otesánek embodied for people.

469
00:46:05,560 --> 00:46:07,430
He's not just a monster who scares kids.

470
00:46:21,400 --> 00:46:24,430
